    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-04-18T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-04-18T19:00:00-05:00" n="1096"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1096">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">831.24/4–146</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Corrigan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">u.s. urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-04-18T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 18, 1946—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>179. For the Ambassador. Major Calderón accompanied by Falcon Briceño and Colonel
                    Marcano left with Flack on April 11 copy of Calderón’s memorandum addressed to
                    General Walsh<note n="36" xml:id="d1096fn36">Maj. Gen. Robert L. Walsh, Army Air
                        Forces.</note> requesting following planes: 6 AT–6’s, 6 AT–11’s, 6 PT–17’s,
                    6 P–47’s, 3 <gloss target="#t_B1">B</gloss>–25’s, 3 Kingfisher hydroplanes, 10
                    C–47’s; also certain maintenance and other equipment and additional air mission
                    personnel. Re Embdes 8575 April 1.</p>
                <p>Final decision on release of these planes, which include bombers, fighters, and
                    advanced trainers (all of which could be made available <pb facs="1338" n="1320"
                        xml:id="pg_1320"/> under interim program) is subject to your approval.
                    Please telegraph your recommendation on foregoing.<note n="37"
                        xml:id="d1096fn37">In telegram 234, April 22, 1 p.m., the Ambassador
                        indicated that the presence of tension between civilian and military
                        elements in Venezuela made necessary a deferring of a decision on releasing
                        planes (831.00/4–2246). Reassured by the President of the Junta, Ambassador
                        Corrigan in telegram 254, May 1, 1946, 5 p.m., concurred in the proposal to
                        release planes, maintenance items, and to add personnel to the air mission
                        (831.24/5–146).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
